<h2 id="when-to-use">When to use tabbed navigation</h2>
<p>Use the tabbed navigation component when users need to move between related pages in a service. For example, if your service is a case management system, you could use tabbed navigation if there are several pages associated with a single case.</p>
<p>It is designed for staff-facing services that staff use repeatedly.</p>

<h2 id="when-not-to-use">When not to use tabbed navigation</h2>
<p>Do not use tabbed navigation as the primary navigation in a service. Use the <a href="/design-system/components/header">header component</a> with the navigation option.</p>
<p>Do not use it on content-heavy public websites. Users may scroll past tabbed navigation on long content pages. To help users navigate content, consider the:</p>
<ul>
    <li><a href="/design-system/patterns/hub-page">hub page pattern</a></li>
    <li><a href="/design-system/patterns/mini-hub">mini hub pattern</a></li> 
</ul>
<p>Do not use this component for links between sections of the same page. If you need to organise large amounts of content on a single page, consider:</p>
<ul>
    <li>cutting the content back</li>
    <li>using headings</li>    
    <li>the <a href="/design-system/components/tabs">tab component</a></li>
    <li><a href="/design-system/components/expander">expanders</a></li>
    <li><a href="/design-system/components/details">details</a></li>
</ul>

<p>The tab component, expanders and details hide sections of content on a page which a user can choose to reveal.</p>
<p>Another form of secondary navigation is side navigation. If you want to help us develop a side navigation component, you can contribute via the side navigation GitHub issue in the design system backlog [create issue and link].</p>

<h2 id="how-to-use">How to use tabbed navigation</h2>
<p>Tabbed navigation is a horizontal list of links. On small screens, it displays vertically.</p>
<p>Put the component near the top of the page. Users may not see it if it is further down. You can put it before or after the main heading (<code>&lt;h1&gt;</code>).</p>
<p>If you put the component before your main heading (the <code>&lt;h1&gt;</code>), put it before the <code>&lt;main&gt;</code> element of the page. This means it is skipped when skip link is used.</p>
<p>Tabbed navigation looks like the <a href="/design-system/components/tabs">tabs component</a> but [note how it is different]. Unlike the tabs component, it does not use JavaScript. Each item in the navigation is a link to a separate full page with a different URL. If you use the component for filtering a list or table, update the page's URL with a query string instead.</p>
<p>Unlike main navigation, 1 of the items in tabbed navigation should always be highlighted as the current page. This item remains a link, but uses black text and has a line beneath it. [Amend if need be.]</p>
<p>[Was there something about not displaying in a disabled state?]</p>

<h3>Making page titles and headings unique</h3>
<p>Make sure each page linked from the tabbed navigation has a unique <code>&lt;h1&gt;</code> and a unique browser page title (<code>&lt;title&gt;</code>). This helps screen reader users who navigate by headings know when a page has changed. It also helps users who bookmark a page.</p>
<p>How you do this depends on where you put the tabbed navigation.</p>
<h4>Tabbed navigation above the <code>&lt;h1&gt;</code></h4>
<p>The <code>&lt;h1&gt;</code> on each page can be the name of the tab, for example "Today", "Yesterday" or "Last week". The page title should match.</p>
<p>[Insert example]</p>
<h4>Tabbed navigation below the <code>&lt;h1&gt;</code></h4>
<p>This layout is common when a page is about a specific record or view that you want to keep visible as the user switches tabs, for example a case list filtered by date.</p>
<p>Visually, you may want the same <code>&lt;h1&gt;</code> to appear on every tab. But for accessibility, you must also include something unique to show users which tab's content they are on.</p>
<p>There are 2 ways to do this.</p>
<h5>Hidden text</h5>
<p>Keep the visual heading as-is and add a hidden span after it that names the current tab. Screen readers will announce both parts, while sighted users only see the main heading.</p>
  {{ designExample({
    group: "components",
    item: "tabbed-navigation",
    type: "heading-with-hidden-text",
    htmlOnly: true
  }) }}
<p>The page <code>&lt;title&gt;</code> should also include the tab name, for example: Cases – Today – [Service name].</p>
<p>This works well when the consistent heading is already meaningful context and you just need to make the tab heading unique for assistive technology.</p>
<h5>Caption</h5>
<p>You can use a caption inside the <code>&lt;h1&gt;</code> to provide context, with the tab name as the caption.</p>
<p>The caption ("Today") appears visually above the heading text ("Cases") but is part of the same <code>&lt;h1&gt;</code> element, so screen readers announce it as a single heading.</p>
  {{ designExample({
    group: "components",
    item: "tabbed-navigation",
    type: "heading-with-caption",
    htmlOnly: true
  }) }}
<p>The page <code>&lt;title&gt;</code> should still be unique, for example: Today – Cases – [Service name].</p>

<h3 id="labelling-and-ordering-items">Labelling and ordering items</h3>
<p>Consider how many items to include in the navigation. Take into account label (link text) length and how the navigation overflows or displays responsively. Keep labels as short as possible.</p>
<p>Make sure that the label matches the heading of the page it links to.</p> 
<p>Decide on the default item to load. Generally it's best to order items from most to least used, with the most-used item being the first in the list and the one that's open by default. However, you can choose a different order. For example, if there is a chronological or workflow order, the first in the list may not the most useful one to display by default.</p>
